<h2 style="font-size:34px">Motorbike fines in Nha Trang in 2026 (Decree 168)</h2>
<img src="img/article/cover-shtrafy.jpg" alt="Rider with a helmet on a road in Vietnam" class="lead-img">
<p>Since 1 January 2025 Vietnam enforces <b>Decree 168/2024</b> — traffic fines went up sharply and police (and cameras) got stricter. As a tourist on a bike it pays to know this so you don&rsquo;t hand over half your holiday budget for nothing. Here&rsquo;s the plain version for 2026.</p>
<h2>First, what matters for 50cc</h2>
<p>A <b>50cc bike needs no licence</b> — that&rsquo;s legal. Decree 168 also introduced a <b>licence points system</b> (violations deduct points; hit the limit and your licence is revoked). <b>But on a 50cc you have no licence</b> — so there are no points to lose, the system doesn&rsquo;t touch you. The <b>monetary fine, however, you pay either way.</b> So the amounts are what matter.</p>
<h2>Common violations and amounts (motorbike)</h2>
<ul>
<li><b>No helmet</b> (or chin strap not fastened) — <b>400,000–600,000 ₫</b>. Both rider and passenger are fined. Kids under 6 are exempt. This is the #1 thing tourists get caught for.</li>
<li><b>Running a red light</b> — <b>4,000,000–6,000,000 ₫</b>. Crossing the stop line without going through — 200,000–400,000 ₫.</li>
<li><b>Phone in hand while riding</b> — <b>800,000–1,000,000 ₫</b>.</li>
<li><b>Red light causing a crash</b> — <b>10,000,000–14,000,000 ₫</b>.</li>
<li><b>Drink-riding</b> — the strictest. Riding under the influence brings very large fines (millions of ₫) and vehicle seizure. Vietnam does not joke about alcohol and bikes — don&rsquo;t risk it at all.</li>
</ul>
<p><i>Amounts are per Decree 168/2024; they may be updated over time, but this is the ballpark.</i></p>
<h2>What tourists get caught for most</h2>
<p>By enforcement stats it&rsquo;s the <b>helmet</b> (#1 — fasten that strap!), <b>bike papers</b> (carry them), and <b>red light / wrong way</b>. Nha Trang police run checks on key streets and along the seafront from time to time.</p>
<h2>How to stay clear — quick checklist</h2>
<ul>
<li>Always <b>helmet + fastened strap</b>, rider and passenger.</li>
<li>Carry the <b>bike papers</b> (cà vẹt) — original or copy.</li>
<li><b>Never drink</b> and ride.</li>
<li>No red lights, wrong way or pavements — cameras keep spreading.</li>
</ul>
<h2>Where we come in</h2>
<p>We sell bikes with <b>clean papers, checked against the police database</b> — so you won&rsquo;t get a &ldquo;no papers&rdquo; or &ldquo;wrong bike&rdquo; fine. And they&rsquo;re real <b>50cc — legal without a licence</b>. All that&rsquo;s left is to put on a helmet and ride easy.</p>
